SIMPLE: encore
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Encore
<hw>En`core"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv. ⟦or⟧ interj.</pos> <ety>[F.
The last part of the word is fr. L. <ets>hora</ets> hour. See
<er>Hour</er>.]</ety> <def>Once more; again; -- used by the auditors and
spectators of plays, concerts, and other entertainments, to call for a
repetition of a particular part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Encore
<hw>En`core"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A call or demand (as, by continued
applause) for a repetition; <as>as, the <ex>encores</ex> were
numerous</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Encore
<hw>En`core"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Encored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Encoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To call for a repetition or
reappearance of; <as>as, to <ex>encore</ex> a song or a
singer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Rebecca] insisted upon <qex>encoring</qex> one of the duets.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Encorporing</ent>⟦br⟧
